Let&#39;s start with what you&#39;re trying to achieve. You have a Composite class that consists of an `Employee` and an `Address`. You want to create a list of `Employee` objects with their corresponding `Address` objects from a `yaml` configuration file.

To do this, you&#39;ll need to define your yaml properties in a specific way that matches the structure of your Composite class. Here&#39;s an example of what your yaml file could look like:

    employees:
      - name: John Doe
        department: Sales
        address:
          street: 123 Main St
          houseNo: 4A
          postCode: 12345
      - name: Jane Smith
        department: Marketing
        address:
          street: 456 Elm St
          houseNo: 10B
          postCode: 67890

In this yaml file, you have a property called `employees`, which is a list of `Employee` objects. Each `Employee` object has a `name`, `department`, and an `address` object. The `address` object also has its own `street`, `houseNo`, and `postCode` properties.

To load this yaml file at the start of the application, you&#39;ll need to create a configuration class that maps the yaml properties to a list of `Employee` objects. Here&#39;s an example of what that configuration class could look like:

    @Configuration
    @ConfigurationProperties(prefix = &quot;employees&quot;)
    public class EmployeeConfig {
        private List&lt;Employee&gt; employeeList;
    
        public List&lt;Employee&gt; getEmployeeList() {
            return employeeList;
        }
    
        public void setEmployeeList(List&lt;Employee&gt; employeeList) {
            this.employeeList = employeeList;
        }
    }

In this configuration class, we use the `@ConfigurationProperties` annotation to specify the prefix of our yaml properties, which is `employees`. We also have a field called `employeeList` of type `List&lt;Employee&gt;`, which will be populated with the yaml properties at startup.

To use this `EmployeeConfig` class in other parts of your application, you can simply inject it as a dependency. For example, you could create a `RestController` that returns the list of `Employee` objects as JSON:

    @RestController
    public class EmployeeController {
        private final EmployeeConfig employeeConfig;
    
        public EmployeeController(EmployeeConfig employeeConfig) {
            this.employeeConfig = employeeConfig;
        }
    
        @GetMapping(&quot;/employees&quot;)
        public List&lt;Employee&gt; getEmployees() {
            return employeeConfig.getEmployeeList();
        }
    }

In this `RestController`, we inject the `EmployeeConfig` class as a dependency in the constructor. We then create a `GET` endpoint that returns the list of `Employee` objects. When this endpoint is hit, Spring Boot will automatically populate the `employeeConfig` field with the yaml properties and return the list of `Employee` objects.

