You don&#39;t want to store the binary value in an int as most binary values would be too large for this.  Also, consider the value &quot;100110110101&quot;.  When you convert to an it, the method presumes it is a **decimal** value.  So it is really 100,110,110,101 in `base 10` which far exceeds the value that an `int` can store.  So you will get a `NumberFormatException` from `Integer.parseInt()` since it is not a valid `int` (it&#39;s too large).  If the length is exactly `32` and the high order is set, result will be negative in keeping with two&#39;s complement representation.
  
So just use the String as passed to the method. 
```
System.out.println(binaryToDecimal(&quot;110101100110110101&quot;));
```
prints
```
219573
```
- iterate over the string and get the binary digit as an int (this uses codePoints to catch various character encodings).
- multiplying by 2 makes &quot;space&quot; to &quot;append&quot; the next digit using addition.
- then return the result.
```
public static int binaryToDecimal(String str) {
    int len = str.length();     
    if (len &gt; 32) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException(
                &quot;\nBinary string exceeds allowable width (%d)&quot;
                        .formatted(len));
    }
    int result = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; len; i++) {
        int bit = Character.digit(str.codePointAt(i),2);
        if (bit != -1) {
            result = result * 2 + bit;
        } else {
            throw new NumberFormatException(
                    &quot;Non-binary character &#39;%c&#39; found in %s.&quot;.formatted(str.charAt(i), str));
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```
An exception will be thrown if a non-binary digit is encountered.

