For the ```@Autowired``` annotation according to documentation 
&gt; Fields are injected right after construction of a bean, before any config methods are invoked. Such a config field does not have to be public.
Autowired Methods.

So for property autowiring it will create a object of the class using default consructor and only after the object is created the dependencies are injected . So in your case in ```CustomLogger``` during object creation the ```myConfig``` is not injected yet and so it is null which leads to NPE.


This can be resolved by going for dependency injection using constructors

```java
@Component
public class CustomLogger {
    private final String env;
    private final LoggerConfig myConfig;
    @Autowired
    // Note : @Autowired is not really necessary for constructor autowiring in newer versions of spring
    public CustomLogger(LoggerConfig config) {
        this.myConfig = config;
        this.env = myConfig.env;  
    }
}
```
in which case the object is created along with its dependencies

